AFTER THE VALVE WAS SECURED THE CAR WAS RECHECKED FOR LEAKS, FINDING NONE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

THE CONTAINMENT POOL WAS ATTACHED TO THE CAR AND THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE ISOLATION TRACK FOR TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TANK CAR.  RHODIA PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND TOOK CHARGE OF THE SCENE AND DID THE TRANSFER.

THE DRUM FELL  OFF THE TRUCK ONTO THE HOSPITAL'S PAVED PARKING LOT LAND UPSIDE DOWN ON THE EDGE OF THE DRUM RING CAUSE THE LID TO COME OFF AND SPILLING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF N53 GALLONS. USING THE SPILL KIT CARRIED ON THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF HOSPITAL EMPLOYEES CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENTS PLACED ON THE PARKING TO A HOLDING PONDS. THE SPILL APPEARED TO BE CONTAINED WITHIN THE DRAIN. THE HOLDING POND WAS DRY AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, BUT IT BEGAN TO RAIN WHILE AWAITING THE ARRIVAL OF A VACUUM TRUCK FOR 4 HOURS. MATERIAL FROM THE DRAIN AND RAINWATER AND SLUDGE WHICH ACCUMULATED IN THE HOLDING POND WERE PUMPED INTO THE VACUUM TRUCK AND THEN TRANSFERRED TO DRUMS. SEVENTEEN DRUMS OF WASTE WERE GENERATED, LO DRUMS OF RAINWATER AND SOLVENT AND 7 DRUMS OF ABSORBENTS AND SLUDGE. WASTE WAS MANIFESTED AND DELIVERED TO ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS IS DISCUSSING PROPER USE OF DRUM DOLLIES WITH ITS DRIVERS AND WAREHOUSE WORKERS.

column168: I GOT A CALL ABOUT A LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID IN FEEDER AT DOOR SIX FROM PAUL PELLETIER, USING PROPER PPE, DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. I WENT TO GET IT. SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO BOX.  NO CLEANUP WAS NEEDED. BROUGHT BACK TO DMP CAGE TO PROCESS.  ALL CANS WERE CONTAMINATED SO THEY WERE SOLIDIFIED.

TRAILER HAD JUST COMPLETED HM183 INSPECTIONS AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE, DRIVER CONNECTED DISCHARGE LINES TO CUSTOMER AND WAS ASSURED BY CUSTOMER PERSONNEL THAT ALL CUSTOMER VALVES WERE OPEN.  DRIVER APPLIED AIR TO TRAILER, AND UPON REACHING APPROXIMATELY 15 PSI INTERNAL PRESSURE, THE DOME GASKET FAILED IN A SMALL AREA, SPRAYING APPROX 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT OVER A 20' X 20' AREA.  UNLOADING ACTIVITIES WERE IMMEDIATELY CEASED.  GASKET WAS REPAIRED AND UNLOADING RESUMED. ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, INC OF TEMPE, AZ WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL AS THE AREA WAS GRAVEL AND SAND AND SIMPLE NEUTRALIZATION AND ABSORPTION WAS NOT FEASIBLE.  APPROXIMATELY 10 YARDS OF SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS AS NON-HAZARDOUS, NON-RCRA WASTE.  INVESTIGATION INTO THE GASKET FAILURE IS CURRENTLY BEING CONDUCTED.

THE LIGHTS WERE FLASHING INSTEAD OF GOING THRU THE NORMAL GREEN/YELLOW/RED SEQUENCE. OUR DRIVER HAD STOPPED AND PROCEEDED THRU THE INTERSECTION WHEN THE OV CAME THRU AND STRUCK OUR TRUCK. THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AS TO WHERE THE OV HAD SUDDENLY APPEARED FROM AND IF HE DID INDEED HAVE THE SAME FLASHING RED LIGHT THAT OUR DRIVER HAD. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WERE ON THE SCENE AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, BUT WAS NOT NEEDED. THE FILLER VALVE SHEARED WAS SHEARED OFF THE MOTOR FUEL TANK. LESS THAN 5 GAL RELEASE AS TANK WAS CLOSE TO BEING EMPTY. NO BI. NO EVACUATION. THE WESTERLY PORTION OF WOODLAWN ST WAS CLOSED FOR APPROX 2 HRS UNTIL THE FUEL TANK WAS BLED  OFF OF ITS REMAINING FUEL (AGAIN LESS THAN 5 GALS). column168: OUR LA ROCHE EMPLOYEE WAS DISPATCHED TO KOP-FLEX IN HANOVER MD TO MAKE A TANK TRUCK DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:20 PM ON THURS. 5-14-1998 THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE DELIVERY HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER'S TANK.  HE ENGAGED THE POWER  TAKE OFF UNIT AND PUMP.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY E MINUTES AMMONIA BEGAN TO RELEASE FROM THE WEEP HOLE OF THE PUMP AND DISCHARGED APPROXIMATELY 5 LBS OF AMMONIA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ENGAGED THE EMERGENCY SUT-VALVE AND STOPPED THE FLOW AND PUMP.  THE FOLLOWING DAY WE INSPECTED THE PUMP AND FOUND LOOSE SEALS HOWEVER THIS WAS NOT THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A BROKEN VALVE STEAM IN THE VALVE BODY OF THE HOSE REEL CREATED A BLOCKAGE, THUS  CAUSING BACK PRESSURE ON THE PUMP.

THE DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD TRAILER.  OPENED FIREVALVE, DID NOT NOTICE THAT UNLOADING VALVE WAS OPENED PARTIALLY.  STARTED PULLING CAP FROM HOSE END.  HYDROSTATIC PRESSURE FROM TRAILER BEING FULL CAUSED CRUDE OIL SPRAY OUT, RESULTING IN A THREE GALLON SPILL.  THE NECESSARY CLEANUP WAS HANDLED.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT LIKE THIS, TRAINING WAS DONE WITH ALL EMPLOYEES TO MAKE SURE THEY CHECK T SEE IF ALL VALVES ARE CLOSED BEFORE PULLING END CAPS.

THEY VISUALLY CHECKED THE LIQUID LEVEL IN THE TANK AND FOUND THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL. FERGUSON OFF LOADED 5, 55 GALLON DRUMS OF PRODUCT FROM THE CAR. THEY ALSO FOUND THE CAR HAD NO MANWAY COVER GASKET.  FERGUSON INSTALLED A NEW GASKET & THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DEMOBILIZED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

WE WERE ABLE TO CONTACT OUR DRIVER AND DIVERT HIM FROM HIS ROUTE TO OUR TERMINAL.  PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER PRODUCT ONTO A RUBBER-LINED TRAILER BEING BROUGHT IN FROM ANOTHER TERMINAL. BEFORE THIS COULD BE DONE, THE TRAILER BURST DUE TO BUILT UP PRESSURE GENERATED BY THE CHEMICAL REACTION OF THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT AND THE ALUMINUM TRAILER.

column168: DRIVER LEFT LNO SERVICE CENTER TO DELIVER 12 CYLINDERS TO 5729 SALEM IN HARAHAN. WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO UNLOAD, THE PALLET THE CYLINDERS WERE ATOP FAILED.  THIS CAUSED THE CYLINDERS TO LEAN OVER AGAINST EACH OTHER.  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD, THE CUSTOMER STATED THEY HEARD A "HISSING" NOISE.  THE CUSTOMER NOTIFIED LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES ENTERED TRAILER WITH PROPER EQUIPMENT AND DID NOT HEAR ANY NOISE.  AT 1600 A MONITORING DEVICE WAS USED TO DETECT ANY LEAKING.  THERE WAS NONE AT THIS TIME. CON-WAY CALLED IN AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP TEAM. WHEN THEY ARRIVED AT 1700, THE MONITOR WAS USED TO CHECK EACH INDIVIDUAL CYLINDER. THERE WAS NO DETECTION OUTSIDE THE CYLINDERS, BUT WHEN THE MONITOR WAS PLACED INSIDE THE COVER OF THE CYLINDER, A LEAK WAS DETECTED IN 3 CYLINDERS.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP TEAM UNLOADED AND PLACED ALL CYLINDERS IN THE WAREHOUSE OF THE CUSTOMER.  EACH CYLINDER WAS CHECKED AGAIN.  ONLY ONE CYLINDER WAS DETECTED TO HAVE A LEAK, AGAIN ONLY BEING DETECTIBLE IN THE COVER OF THE CYLINDER.  THE CYLINDER WAS CAPPED AND SHIPPED TO  THE VAN WATER & ROGERS LOCATED AT 34200 VW & R IN GEISMER, LA.

ON MAY 21, 1998 AT APPROXIMATELY 0315 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, UTLX99095, LOADED WITH AMMONIA ANHYDROUS , LIQUEFIED, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED FROM THE SHIPPER'S INDUSTRY PLANT BEAUMONT, TX. ONE KCS EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND WAS TAKEN TO THE BEAUMONT MEDICAL & SURGICAL HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION. THE KCS EMPLOYEE WAS EXAMINED BY THE ATTENDING PHYSICIAN AND RELEASED WITH NO MEDICAL PROBLEMS FOUND.  THE TANK CAR WAS LEFT AT THE INDUSTRY SIDING TRACK AND THE SHIPPER ( RESPONSIBLE PARTY ) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW AND DETERMINED THAT A MAIN LOADING VALVE HAD MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING THE LEAK.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN OFF LOADED BY THE PLANT FOR IMMEDIATE REPAIR OF THE DEFECTIVE VALVE.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY COMPLETED UPON DISCOVERY OF THE INCIDENT.

On may 15,1998, at approximately 0445 hours,  a railroad tank car, gatx 11468, loaded with cresols, was observed leaking from top of the car was being switched at KCS shreveport, louisiana rail yard.  The tank car was leaking from a defective dome lid and leaked only when moved.  Therefore, the tank car was immediately isolate to kcs track number 45 to prevent further movement and possible leakage.  The tanK car released approximately 1 gallon of material which was contained to the sides of the tank car and did not contact the ground.  No injuries or exposures resulted from this release.  The shipper (responsible party) was immediately notified and dispatched a repair crew to the site.  all appropriate state and federal notifications were immediately completed.  upon completion of tank car repairs and decontamination by the shipper the tank car was then released for destination.

THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DG SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING F.A.A. INVESTIGATION.  THE F.A.A. WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE SHIPMENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, THE DRIVER EXPERIENCED AN OVERFLOW AT THE FILL BOX, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) GALLONS OF GAS ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD SURROUNDING THE FILL PART. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REMOTE FILL SYSTEM CONTAINS PIPING SIZES THAT ARE INSUFFICIENT FOR HANDLING THE DISCHARGE RATES GENERATED BY OUR DELIVERY TRUCKS IF DISCHARGE VALVES ARE OPENED TO 100%. THE SYSTEM IS SCHEDULED TO BE REPLACED IN DECEMBER 1998. UNTIL THAT TIME, DRIVERS WILL CUT BACK THE RATE AT WHICH THEY DROP PRODUCT AT THIS FACILITY TO AVOID FUTURE SPILL INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE. ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: ON MAY 19,1998, FOUR 55 GALLON POLYETHYLENE CONTAINERS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUIDS WERE LOADED AT ENGINEERED CONTROL SYSTEMS IN WHITSETT, NORTH CAROLINA.  WHILE TRAVELING ENROUTE TO MAGNETTI MARELLI INSANFORD, NORTH CAROLINA, THE DRIVERS NOTICED A LOUD BANG FROM THE VAN PORTION OF THE STRAIGHT TRUCK.  THE TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATLY MOVED TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD TO INVESTIGATE THE NOISE.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS OF THE TRUCK, THE DRIVERS NOTICED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND THE LOAD LOCK BARS HAD FALLEN OUT OF POSITION.  AFTER CONFIRMING THAT THE SHIFTED CONTAINERS WERE NOT DAMAGED OR LEAKING EACH CONTAINER WAS REPOSITIONED AND SECURED FOR TRANSIT. THE DRIVERS PROCEED ED TO THE NEXT PICK-UP LOCATION.  UPON ENTERING MAGNETTI MARELLI'S PARKING LOT, THE STRAIGHT TRUCK CROSSED OVER TWO SPEED BUMPS AND PROCEEDED APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS TO THE WASTE STORAGE AREA.  AFTER EXINTING THE TRUCK THE DRIVERS NOTICED THAT SOME LIQUID MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  UPON OPENING THE TRUCK DOORS, THE DRIVERS NOTICED THAT FOUR CONTAINERS APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED AFTER CROSSING OVER THE SPEED BUMPS IN THE PARKING LOT. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF WASTE MATERIALS LEAKED INSIDE THE TRUCK FLOOR.  THE LIDS AND LID RINGS OF THESE DRUMS WERE APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE WHICH ALLOWED THE LIQUID WASTE MATERIAL TO SLOSH OUT OF THE DRUMS AFTER CROSSING THE SPEED BUMPS.  THE AFFECTED AREAS OF THE PARKING LOT WERE DECONTAMINATED WITH A DECONTAMINATION SOLUTION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL INSIDE THE TRUCK WAS ALSO ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND THE FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED.  THE FOUR LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN UN APPROVED "SALVAGE DRUMS"  AND SECURED IN THE TRUCK.  IN THE FUTURE, THE DRIVERS WILL THOROUGHLY INSPECT THE LOAD LOCK BARS FOR DEFECTS IN ORDER TO PREVENT LOADS FROM SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT. CONTAINER CLOSURE DEVICES WILL ALSO BE MORE CLOSELY MONITORED BY THE DRIVERS AT EACH PICK-UP.

(4) 55 GAL DRUMS OF THE PRODUCT WERE OVERPACKED BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW (FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL) 2 DRUMS WERE ACTUALLY LEAKING AND 2 HAD QUESTIONABLE PACKAGE INTEGRITY.  THE DRUMS WERE BENT BEYOND DOT STANDARDS AND WERE DAMAGED EITHER BY BARREL GRABBER DURING LOADING OR MISTREATMENT IN THE STORAGE WAREHOUSE.  4 DRUMS CONTAINING PPE DEBRIS & PRODUCT SPILLAGE ARE BEING DISPOSED OF ON BEHALF OF FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL.
NO REMARKS

column168: ONE OF THE PACKAGES IN THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS IT WAS PAINT. THE FLASH POINT LISTED ON THE LABEL OF THE INNER PACKAGE WAS 80 DEGREES FARENHEIT. AS THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENT AS DANGEROUS GOODS IT WAS REPORTED TO F.A.A. AGENT AL KLUKOWSKI AS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER, SEE ENCLOSED, AND THE FLASH POINT WAS LISTED AS 110 DEGREES FARENHEIT. DURING A PHONE CONVERSATION WITH BETH BULKE, SAFETY MANAGER AT THE SHIPPER'S COMPANY, THE 80 DEGREE F FLASH POINT IS WHEN IT'S MIXED WITH A CATALYST. THE FLASH POINT FOR THIS PAINT THAT HAD NOT BEEN MIXED WITH ANYTHING WOULD BE 100 DEGREES FARENHEIT. THERE ARE 16 PIECES IN THIS CONSIGNMENT. I DID NOT ASK THE FEDEX STATION PERSONNEL TO OPEN EACH ONE. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT FEDEX PENDING F.A.A. INVESTIGATION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED. THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING AND HAD A STRONG COSMESTIC TYPE OF ODOR. THIS PROMPTED HANDLING PERSONNEL TO STOP THE SHIPMENT AND NOTIFY THE DG SPILL SPECIALIST ON DUTY AT THE TIME. THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES OF COSMETICS ONE OF WHICH WAS LEAKING. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER FOR BOTH OF THE ITEMS SHIPPED IN THE PACKAGE. ONE OF THE ITEMS WAS NON HAZ. THE COMMODITY THAT LEAKED HOWEVER WAS A COSMESTIC WITH AN ACETONE BASE AND A FLASH POINT OF 74 DEGREES. THERE WERE NO HAZ MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: ON 9 MAY 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 - 1330 HOURS, AT SEA-TAC INTL. AIRPORT, AMERICAN AIRLINES TRANSFERRED TO ALASKA AIRLINES A CHECKED BAG (A FIBREBOARD BOX APPRX 2"SQ) BELONGING TO MR. VICTOR VEROSTA (BAG TAG #AA874499)). WHILE AN ALASKA BAGGAGE HANDLER WAS MOVING THE BOX FROM THE CONVEYOR BELT TO A BAGGAGE CART, A LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE BOX ONTO THE AGENTS LEG, CAUSING IT TO TURN WHITE AND ITCH. THE BOX HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE SMOKE AND FUMES COMING FROM WITHIN. THE SEA-TAC AMERICAN AIRLINES STATION MANAGER WAS ADVISED. THE PASSENGER WAS CONTACTED AND THE PORT OF SEATTLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE BAGGAGE RAMP MAKE-UP AREA. THE BOX WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 3-16 OUNCE @ UNDECLARED PLASTIC BOTTLES 35% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE. IN THE BOX WERE TEN (10)-CYBER POWER COMPUTER SURGE PROTECTORS AND PERSONAL ITEMS SUCH AS SHOES, ARTICLES OF CLOTHING AND 2 PLASTIC BOTTLES OF BODY LOTION. THE CONTENTS OF ONE OF THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE BOTTLES HAD EMPTIED AND THE ITEMS WITHIN THE BOX RECEIVED DAMAGE. THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE BOX DID NOT RECEIVE ANY DAMAGE IN THAT THE CONTENTS ABSORBED THE LIQUID. THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX WERE SOAKED WITH WATER TO DILUTE THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE TO RENDER IT SAFE. THE ALASKA AIRLINE AGENT WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EMERGENCY TREATMENT AND RELEASED. THE AGENT RETURNED TO WORK. THE PASSENGER CONTINUED HIS TRIP TO FAIRBANKS ALASKA. THE NON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO MR. VEROSTA ON OR ABOUT 18 MAY 98

column168: THIS IS A UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT. ON 5/2/98 AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177,  AN ODOR WAS REPORTED ON OUR "ALPHA RAMP".  ON AIRCRAFT FLIGHT 369, TAIL NUMBER N828AX, IN BELLY 3 OF THE AIRCRAFT.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE DISCOVERED A 20 GALLON RUBBER MAID PLASTIC RECEPTACLE.  THE OUTER RECEPTACLE HAD NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS TO CONTAIN A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE TOP OF THE RECEPTACLE HAD ONLY A LIBRA LABEL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS HE DISCOVERED THE FOLLOWING:  14  X 4 OZS OF RED EYE - FLAMMABLE, IN PLASTIC RECEPTACLES THAT WERE NOT FULL AND DID NOT LEAK.  1 X 32 OZS - LEATHER DYE - FLAMMABLE, IN PLASTIC RECEPTACLES, THESE DID NOT LEAK.  1 X 10 OZS - LEATHER DYE - FLAMMABLE, IN A GLASS RECEPTACLE, DID NOT LEAK.  2 X 32 OZS - PETROLEUM DISTILLATES - FLAMMABLE, GLASS RECEPTACLES, OF WHICH 1 WAS BROKEN.  1 X 11 OZS - LEATHER SHEEN - FLAMMABLE, IN AN AEROSOL METAL RECEPTACLES, COULD NOT DETERMINE IF THIS LEAKED.  1 X 16 OZS - GLASS RECEPTACLE OF RUBBER CEMENT - FLAMMABLE, THIS WAS THE RECEPTACLE THAT WAS THOUGHT TO BE CAUSING THE ODOR, DID NOT LEAK.  THE REPORTED ODOR WAS THOUGHT TO HAVE COME FROM THE RUBBER CEMENT RECEPTACLE, HOWEVER AFTER INSPECTING THE INNER CONTENTS HE FOUND 1 X 32 OUNCE GLASS RECEPTACLE THAT CONTAINED PETROLEUM DISTILLATES THAT WAS BROKEN.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS IMPROPER LOADING OF THE INNER CONTENTS AND NOT ENOUGH  CUSHIONING MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT DID CONTAIN A CLAIM FORM FROM AIRBORNE AND A PERSONAL LETTER TO THE SHIPPER, THIS INFORMATION IS NOT AVAILABLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED AND IS BEING HELD PENDING AN INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

THE BUILDING REMAINED UNDER THE CONTROL OF THE POLICE DEPARTMENT FROM 20:00 TO APPROXIMATELY 22:45. THE ST LOUIS POLICE DEPARTMENT TOOK POSSESSION OF THE PACKAGE. POLICE SAID THE BAGGIES CONTAINED; POTASSIUM PERCLORATE, ALUMINUM POWDER, SULFUR POWDER. THE SHIPPING PAPERS FILED THROUGH UPS CLAIMED THE PACKAGE CONTAINED "VIDEO/AUDIO TAPES"

column168: TRAILER 5-59 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 2000/ 5-3-98 BY MINNEAPOLIS T/O STEELE.  SCI SUPERVISOR, LARRY WATSON AND I ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2130/03 TO INVESTIGATE.  AFTER CALLING THE 800 NUMBER PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER ON THE BILL OF LADING IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER SHOULD REMAIN AS IS UNTIL TERRA SAFETY MANAGER DALE UHL COULD COME E DOWN ON MONDAY A.M.  ON MONDAY, MR. UHL DECIDED TO CALL THE SIOUX CITY FIRE DEPT., SPILL TEAM TO THE SCENE, AFTER THEY UNLOADED THE TRAILER IN THE YARD DOWN TO THE POINT WHERE THE SHIPMENT BEGAN, THEY DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP OF THE NUMBER 1 TOTE.  THE PRO-NUMBERS LOADED ON TOP OF THE TOTE WHERE 836-01205-2 AND 120-94149-4 TOTALING 445 LBS. AFTER REMOVING THE AFFECTED TOTE FROM THE TRAILER, THE TOTE WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND SET ON THE DOCK.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN BACKED INTO THE DOCK AND UNLOADED.  WHILE UNLOADING THE OTHER TWO TOTES IT WAS NOTICED THAT BOTH OF THESE WERE ALSO LEAKING FROM ALL AVAILABLE POINTS ON TOP DUE TO LOOSE/AND OR MISSING SEALS. MR. UHL WAS CALLED AND CAME BACK TO THE C.F. DOCK.  AFTER INSPECTION, HE CALLED THE LOCAL TERRA FACILITY AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL 3 TOTES WOULD BE TAKEN TO THEIR FACILITY TO BE DRAINED AND REPACKAGED.  MR. BOB PICKS WITH TERRA ALSO CAME TO THE C.F. DOCK THAT EVENING.  HE SAID THAT THESE TOTES SHOULD HAVE NEVER BEEN USED AS THEY HAD BEEN FILLED WITH A DIFFERENT PRODUCT PREVIOUSLY AND THAT THE TOTES WERE NOT IN GOOD SHAPE.  HE TOLD ME THAT HE HAD SEEN AN INSTANCE WHERE AN OLD TOTE HAD ACTUALLY SPLIT IN HALF. THAT NEXT MORNING MR. PICK CAME TO THE C.F. DOCK AND ACCEPTED DELIVERY OF THE SHIPMENT. HE STATED AT THIS TIME THAT THE AGE OF ONE OF THE TOTES WAS OVER 10 YEARS, AND THAT THEY ALL SHOULD HAVE BEEN SAID THAT THE FACILITY THAT SHIPPED THESE TOTES WAS RECENTLY PURCHASED BY TERRA WAS NOT QUITE UP TO TERRA STANDARDS YET. THE FINAL ANALYSIS APPEARS TO BE THAT THE SPILL/LEAKAGE WAS A RESULT OF IMPROPER PACKAGING.  TWO OF THE TOTES WERE LEAKING ON THEIR OWN WHILE THE THIRD TOTE, EVEN THOUGH IT HAD TWO OTHERS SHIPMENTS OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF IT, MAY HAVE COMPRESSED DUE TO THE AGE OF THE TOTE RATHER THAT THE WEIGHT ON TOP OF THE TOTE.  JUST MY OBSERVATION.

column168: DRIVER REPORTS HE WAS N/B RT 12 IN THE RIGHT STRAIGHT LANE.  AS HE APPROACHED S. OLD RAND HE OBSERVED THE TRAFFIC LIGHTS WERE NOT WORKING. HE THEN REALIZED THERE WERE STOP SIGNS AS HE ENTERED THE INTERSECTION AT APPROX. 50 MPH.  HE THEN LOCKED UP THE BRAKES AND STRUCK UNIT 2 WHICH WAS CROSSING N/B RT 12 FROM SOUTH OLD RAND.  DRIVER THEN VEERED TO THE LEFT. HE THEN LOST CONTROL OF UNIT 1 AND AIMED FOR THE TREES AT WHICH TIME THE UNIT ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE.  DRIVER 2 REPORTS HE WAS STOPPED ON SOUTH OLD AT RT 12 BEHIND A WHITE CAR.  THE TRAFFIC LIGHTS WERE OUT DUE TO A POWER OUTAGE. SAW UNIT 1 60 THRU THE INTERSECTION N/B RT 12 AT S OLD RANO AT APPROXIMATELY 40 MPH AND STRUCK UNIT 2 WHO WAS EXITING S OLD RAND W/B ONTO S/B RT 12. column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER ON AN EASTBOUND TRAIN LOCATED AT BEAUMONT, CALIFORNIA.  THE FLAT CAR WITH THE CONTAINERS WAS BEING SET OUT AT THE BACK TRACK LOCATED WITHIN THE CITY OF BEAUMONT.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO BEAUMONT AND MET WITH JESSE PEREZ, MANAGER, COMPLIANCE MEASUREMENT, AND TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL, THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  DEVELOPED THE CONTAINERS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WERE ACTUALLY INTERMODAL TANKS ON CHASSIS, WHICH WERE LOADED ON A ARTICULATED FLAT CAR.  AS THE IM TANK WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE TANK AT A RATE OF 25-30 DROPS PER MINUTE, WHICH WAS POOLING ON THE FLAT CAR.  DUE TO THE EXTREMELY HIGH TEMPERATURES IN THE AREA, THE PRODUCT WAS VOLATILIZING OFF BEFORE ANY REACHED THE GROUND.  INSPECTION OF THE TOP PORTION OF THE IM TANK DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKING TO BE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE SRV WAS SITUATED BEHIND THE MANWAY, ON THE LOW END OF THE TANK, AND DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE TANK, THE PRODUCT LEVEL WAS AGAINST THE VALVE. A DRAIN LINE WAS ATTACHED TO THE TANK'S AIR LINE VALVE, AND DRAPED OVER THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND FLAT CAR, THEN INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM PLACED ADJACENT TO THE CAR.  THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS OPENED.  AS THERE WAS NO PRESSURE IN THE TANK, THIS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO GRAVITY FLOW INTO THE DRUM UNTIL THE LEVEL EQUALIZED.  THE DRAIN LINE WAS THEN ATTACHED TO A POGO PUMP, WITH THE TUBE PORTION OF THE PUMP EXTENDED THROUGH THE AIR LINE VALVE INTO THE INTERIOR OF THE TANK.  AFTER REMOVING A TOTAL OF 55 GALLONS FROM THE IM TANK, THE LEAK A THE SRV HAD CEASED, AND THE MANWAY WAS OPENED.  THE PRODUCT LEVEL WAS LOW ENOUGH AT THIS TIME POINT THAT IT WOULD ALLOW FOR REMOVAL OF THE SRV WITHOUT ANY ADDITIONAL LOSS OF PRODUCT.  THE SRV WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED UPON FIELD COMPRESSING THE SEAT OF THE SRV, IT WAS NOTED THE GASKET AT THE SEAT APPEARED TO HAVE HEAVY GROOVES AND RE INSTALLED TO PROTECT THE LADING WHILE ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO LOCATE THE SHIPPER.  SINCE IT WAS A WEEKEND, ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE OF  RECORD MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  ON MONDAY MORNING, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH GUSTAVO KOMEL, MILLER INTEMODAL, CHANNELVIEW, TEXAS, THE OWNER OF THE IM TANK, WHO ARRANGED TO OVERNIGHT A REPLACEMENT SRV.  UPON RECEIPT OF THE REPLACEMENT SRV THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE DEFECTIVE SRV WAS AGAIN REMOVED AND THE NEW SRV INSTALLED.  THE FLAT CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.   NOTIFICATIONS WERE MED TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING  PURPOSES AND ATTEMPTS TO LOCATE THE PRINCIPLE OWNER OF THIS SHIPMENT, ALONG WITH MILLER INTERMODAL, THE PRINCIPLE OWNER OF THE IM TANK.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT, AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, WHICH DID NOT MEET THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY, NO FURTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE DEFECTIVE SRV WAS RETURNED TO MILLER INTERMODAL, AND BASED UPON THE SHIPPERS REQUEST, ARRANGEMENTS WILL BE MADE TO REMOVED THE SI

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ROBERT WILSON, CAR FOREMAN, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING TANK CAR DOWX 6896 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON RECEIVING YARD, LOCATED THE TANK CAR IN YARD TRACK 1153 AND OBSERVED THE TANK CAR LEAKING A STEADY STREAM OF PRODUCT FROM THE CENTER BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CAR, ESTIMATED TO BE 8-10 GALLONS PER HOUR.  BILLING INFORMATION OF THIS CAR SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE A RESIDUE, AND NOT A FULLY LOADED CAR. THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE AT THE WELD THAT ATTACHES THE PROTECTIVE SKID PLATE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED, DUE TO THE TOXIC NATURE OF THE PRODUCT VAPORS.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH ECOLOGY CONTROL, UNION PACIFIC'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND A TEAM AND EQUIPMENT TO ASSIST IN THE REMEDIATION.  DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR IN THE RECEIVING YARD, ACCESS WAS LIMITED, WHICH REQUIRED MOVING THE TANK CAR.  AS THERE WAS A HOSPITAL DIRECTLY NORTH OF THE RECEIVING YARD, IT WAS DETERMINED THE TANK CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE MOVED EAST, WHICH WOULD PLACE THE CAR ADJACENT TO THE MAIN SWITCHING YARD.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL CLOSED INTERSTATE 10 AND THE CEDER AVE., OVERPASS WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED, WHICH WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY 6AM.  THE AREA WHERE THE TANK CAR WAS TO BE SET, WHICH INCLUDED THE REPAIR SHOP, WAS EVACUATED, AND ONCE THE TANK CAR WAS SET TO YARD TRACK 905 AND ENTRY TEAM REMOVED THE VALVING FROM THE PRODUCT LIQUID LINE ON THE TOP OF THE CAR, AND PLACED A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM TO CAPTURE THE LEAKING PRODUCT UNDERNEATH THE CAR. DURING THIS PROCESS, THE LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR STOPPED AND RESTARTED SEVERAL TIMES.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS BROUGHT IN AND SET UP WITH A PVC "STINGER" TO ACCESS ANY FREE PRODUCT THROUGH THE TANK CAR'S LIQUID LINE.   NO PRODUCT WAS OBTAINED DURING THIS PROCESS, WHICH FURTHER CONFIRMED THE TANK CAR LINER HAD FAILED, AND IT APPEARED THAT THE LIQUID WAS BETWEEN THE TANK LINER AND THE TANK SHELL.  SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO PUTTY THE WELD AT THE SIDE PLATE, WHICH ONLY RESULTED IN THE LEAK MOVING TO OTHER AREAS OF THE WELD.  AT THIS POINT, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH LOCAL GATX TANK CAR REPAIR SHOP TO RECEIVE THIS CAR.  THE REPAIR SHOP HAS A CONTAINMENT PIT THAT WOULD ACCOMMODATE THE LEAKING TANK UNTIL IT COULD BE PURGED.  A MAKESHIFT CONTAINMENT SYSTEM WAS CONSTRUCTED UNDER THE TANK CAR TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPREADING OF PRODUCT DURING THE MOVE.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN MOVED AS A SINGLE UNIT WITH A YARD SWITCH ENGINE, AND SET TO THE GATX CONTAINMENT AREA BY 11 PM. TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE CAPTURED DURING THIS EVENT, AND WERE DELIVERED TO THE DOW TERMINAL ISLAND FACILITY, PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.  A 20 YARD ROLL OFF BIN OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND PPE, WILL BE PROFILED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE DIRECTION OF DOW.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS ADVISED BY KEN NAUCLER, CORRIDOR MANAGER, COLTON, CALIFORNIA OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE DELORES YARD IN CARSON, CALIFORNIA.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED GREG JACOBS, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, DELORES YARD, WHO STATED THE WEST END SWITCH CREW WAS MOVING CARS FROM THE #22 YARD TRACK, WHEN THEY OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS LEFT IN THE YARD TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE DELORES YARD AND MET WITH THE  COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO ERE ON SCENE.  THEY WERE UNABLE TO OBSERVED ANY LEAKS FROM THE TANK CAR AND WERE DEPARTING THE AREA.  THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT HEALTH AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MEMBERS WERE ALSO PRESENT ON SITE.  A YARD ENGINE WAS USED TO MOVE THE TANK CAR SEVERAL TIMES, AND WHEN MOVED, PRODUCT WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY NOTED 4 OF THE 8 MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE, AND COULD BE TURN BY HAND.   THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED WITH A WRENCH.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE CAR WAS AGAIN MOVED SEVERAL TIMES AND NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE DETECTED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FRO MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ROBERT SCHUT, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  MANGER SCHUT STATED THAT THE CAR DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN IN THE RECEIVING YARD ON YARD TRACK #1152 WHEN THE DETECTED A SLIGHT CHLORINE ODOR. MGR COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND MET WITH MGR SCHUT, WHO PROVIDED A TRACK LIST WHICH SHOWED THERE WERE THREE TANK CARS IN THE CENTER PORTION OF THE TRAIN, ALL OF WHICH WERE CHLORINE RESIDUE CARS.  THE CAR DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL PROVIDED TANK CAR GATX 16323 AS THE SUSPECTED LEAKER, HOWEVER AFTER INSPECTING ALL THREE OF THE TANK CARS, DEVELOPED TANK CAR ACFX86435 TO BE THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  A VERY FAINT AND INTERMITTENT CHLORINE ODOR WAS DETECTED AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THE CAR.   ATTEMPTS TO LOCATE THE SPECIFIC AREA OF THE RELEASE PROVED FRUITLESS DUE TO THE INTERMITTENT NATURE. IT APPEARED THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM THE SEAL BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY PLATE, BUT THIS COULD NOT BE ISOLATED AND PIN POINTED AS THE SOURCE.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO PROVIDE A CONTACT SOURCE WITH THE TANK CAR OWNER.  MR. BOB THEIS, ELF ATOCHEM NORTH AMERICA, PORTLAND, OREGON, THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AND TANK CAR, LESSEE, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CURRENT CONDITION OF THE CAR.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REQUIRED REPAIRS TO THIS CAR WERE BEYOND THE EXISTING FIELD CAPABILITIES AND ADDITIONAL RESOURCES WOULD BE REQUIRED.   MR. THEIS HAD CONTACTED THE CHLOREP TEAM FROM THE DOW FACILITY IN PITTSBURH, CA.  THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND STATED THEY WOULD STAND BY THE EVENT ELF ATOCHEM WANTED THEM TO RESPOND.  A SHORT TIME LATER, MR. THEIS ADVISED HE HAD CONTACTED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST, LAPORTE, TEXAS, AND THEY WOULD HAVE A TEAM ON SITE THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  AFTER SEVERAL CALLS TO NARROW DOWN THE EXACT ARRIVAL TIME OF THE ERS TEAM, IT WAS DETERMINED THEY WOULD ARRIVE AT THE LOCATION LATE IN THE AFTERNOON. MANAGER COOPER THEN CONTACTED THE GATX REPAIR FACILITY IN RIALTO, AND REQUESTED THAT RESPOND WITH THEIR FIELD REPAIR TRUCK, WHICH CONTAINS VARIOUS HEAVY TOOLS FOR TANK REPAIRS.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE GATX PERSONNEL, ANOTHER ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR WAS MADE, AND AGAIN, NO DIRECT SOURCE OF THE LEAK COULD BE LOCATED.  THEY MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS TORQUED DOWN, AND THAT DID NOT CORRECT THE LEAK.  AS EACH OF THE VALVES WERE TORQUED DOWN, IT WAS NOTED THAT ALL FOUR OF THE SEAT BOLTS FOR EACH VALVE WERE TIGHT  BUT EASILY TORQUED ANOTHER 3/4 OF A TURN.  THE ANGLE VALVES WERE ALSO TIGHTENED, ALONG WITH THE LINE PLUGS, AND THE PACKING GLANDS AT THE VALVE STEMS.  THE CAR WAS THEN REINSPECT AND NO LEAKS COULD BE DETECTED.  IT IS UNKNOWN AT THIS POINT WHAT PIECE WAS ACTUALLY TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE LEAK. WHILE PICKING UP THE TOOLS, ANOTHER CHLORINE ODOR WAS DETECTED FROM GATX16323.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS OPERATING.  THE CAR

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ROBERT SCHUT, MANAGER, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  MANAGER SCHUT STATED THE CAR DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING  AN INBOUND TRAIN IN THE RECEIVING YARD ON YARD TRACK #1152 WHEN THEY DETECTED A SLIGHT CHLORINE ODOR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND MET WITH MANAGER SCHUT, WHO PROVIDED A TRACK LIST WHICH SHOWED THERE WERE THREE(3) TANK CARS IN THE CENTER PORTION OF THE TRAIN, ALL OF WHICH WERE CHLORINE RESIDUE CARS.  THE CAR DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL PROVIDED TANK CAR GATX 16323 AS THE SUSPECT LEAKER, HOWEVER, AFTER INSPECTING ALL THREE(3) OF THE TANK CARS, DEVELOPED TANK CAR ACFX86435 TO BE THE LEAKING CAR.  A VERY FAINT AND INTERMITTENT CHLORINE ODOR WAS DETECTED AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSE OF THE CAR.  ATTEMPTS TO LOCATED THE SPECIFIC AREA OF THE RELEASE PROVED FRUITLESS DUE TO THE INTERMITTENT NATURE.  IT APPEARED THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM THE SEAL BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY PLATE, BUT THIS COULD NOT BE ISOLATED AND PIN POINTED AS THE SOURCE.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO PROVIDE A CONTACT SOURCE WITH THE TANK CAR OWNER.  MR. BOB THEIS, ELF ATOCHEM NORTH AMERICA, PORTLAND, OREGON, THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AND TANK CAR LESSEE, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CURRENT CONDITION OF THE CAR.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REQUIRED REPAIRS TO THIS CAR WERE BEYOND THE EXISTING FIELD CAPABILITIES AND ADDITIONAL RESOURCES WOULD BE REQUIRED.  MR. THEIS HAD CONTACTED THE CHLOREP TEAM FROM THE DOW FACILITY IN PITTSBURH, CALIFORNIA.  THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND STATED THEY WOULD STAND BY IN THE EVENT ELF ATOCHEM WANTED THEM TO RESPOND.  A SHORT TIME LATER, MR. THEIS ADVISED THAT HE HAD CONTACTED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST, LA PORT, TEXAS, AND THEY WOULD HAVE A TEAM ON SITE THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  AFTER SEVERAL CALLS TO NARROW DOWN THE EXACT ARRIVAL TIME OF THE ERS TEAM, IT WAS DETERMINED THEY WOULD ARRIVE AT THE LOCATION LATE AFTERNOON.  MANAGER COOPER THEN CONTACTED THE GATX REPAIR FACILITY IN RIALTO, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND WITH THEIR FIELD REPAIR TRUCK, WHICH CONTAINS VARIOUS HEAVY TOOLS FOR TANK REPAIRS.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE GATX PERSONNEL, ANOTHER ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR WAS MADE, AND AGAIN, NO DIRECT SOURCE OF THE LEAK COULD BE LOCATED.  THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS TORQUED DOWN AND THAT DID NOT CORRECT THE LEAK.  AS EACH OF THE VALVES WERE TORQUED DOWN, IT WAS NOTED THAT ALL FOUR(4) OF THE SEAT BOLTS FOR EACH VALVE WERE TIGHT, BUT WERE EASILY TORQUED ANOTHER 3/4 OF A TURN.  THE ANGLE VALVES WERE ALSO TIGHTENED ALONG WITH THE LINE PLUGS, AND THE PACKING GLANDS AT THE VALVE STEMS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RE INSPECTED AND NO LEAKS COULD BE DETECTED.  IT IS UNKNOWN AT THIS POINT WHAT PIECE WAS ACTUALLY TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE LEAK. WHILE PICKING UP THE TOOLS, ANOTHER CHLORINE ODOR WAS DETECTED FROM GATX16323. A UPS PACKAGE CAR DRIVER, STEVE BUTTERFIELD, DISCOVERED A LEAKING PACKAGE WITH A 5-PART FORM ON HIS PACKAGE CAR. HE NOTIFIED HIS CENTER. HIS CENTER THEN NOTIFIED MIKE STECKLER (SAFETY DEPARTMENT)WHO RESPONDED TO THE ON ROAD SPILL. MIKE CLEANED UP AND RETREIVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS,CONTAINED THEM AND RETURNED THEM TO THE SALT LAKE CITY HUB. JEFF HUTCHINGS (1ST RESPONDER)RECEIVED CONTAMINATED MATERIALS. ALL SALVAGABLE MATERIAL WAS RE-PACKED USING A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE PROCESSED THROUGH DMP. DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS AND ALL PPE WERE USED.

RESPONDER TO THE SPILL/DONNED PPE PROCESSED VIA THE DMP PROGRAM. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE. LOOSE CAPS CAUSED LEAKAGE PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES. I WORE THE PROPER P.P.E. FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE SHEET GUIDELINES. PRELOAD MANAGER SHOULD REVIEW PACKAGE HANDLING PROCEDURES. PROCESSED WITH WITH CLAYBASE AND NEUTRALIZED/TESTED WITH TAPE CORROSIVE LIQUID ABSORBED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 14:02 PM W.M. SEABAUGH REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER ADVISING TANK CAR ACFX 94283 LOCATED UPRR YARD PHOENIX,AZ WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET. RMCC ADVISED TO CONTACT ALBERT VALDENERGO, CAR FOREMAN FOR ON SITE ASSISTANCE. MR.DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY,TUCSON, AZ WAS ATTEMPTING SCHOOL IN TEXAS. 14:50 SEABAUGH ADVISED BY RMCC THAT MR.VALDENERGO WAS ATTEMPTING TO CONTACT SUPERVISOR FOR AUTHORITY TO RESPOND AND HANDLE. SEABAUGH SPOKE TO ROGER GRANT, UPRR YARDMASTER, 602-257-2530 AT 15:00. MR.GRANT ADVISED SEABAUGH THAT TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AWAY FROM RAILROAD EMPLOYEES AND THAT A BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER TANK CAR  TO CONTAIN LEAKAGE. MR. GRANT FURTHER ADVISED THAT RATE OF LEAKAGE ESTIMATED AT ONE DROP PER MINUTE. WITH MR.JOHNSON AWAY AT SCHOOL SEABAUGH CONTACTED WESTERN REGION CTS FOR ASSISTANCE. SEABAUGH ALSO IN COMMUNICATION WITH SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE PHILLIP LUZMOOR 307-872-6531. AT 16:25 MR.LUZMOOR ADVISED SEABAUGH THAT HE WOULD ASK CONSIGNEE TO RESPOND. AT 17:55 SEABAUGH ADVISED BY UPRR YARDMASTER PHOENIX,AZ 602-257-2540 THAT MR.VALDENERGO HAS RECEIVED AUTHORITY TO RESPOND RESULTING IN TAN CAR BEING SECURED (BOTTOM OUTLET CAP MADE TOOL TIGHT) AT 16:00 CENTRAL TIME. 17:56 SEABAUGH ADVISED WESTER REGION CTS THAT PROBLEM WAS HANDLED.

USED DECISION TREE, USED PPR, IDENTIFIED AS A CORROSIVE BY MARKINGS, NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED WITH SODIUM BICARBONTE, REMOVED PACKAGE TO PROCESSING AREA, WHERE THE DAMAGED CONTENTS WERE RTS'D. THE CONTAIMINATED MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF USING THE UPS DMP PROGRAM.

PACKAGE WAS ON CONVEYOR BELT AND I HAD JUST COME ONTO THE BELT FROM THE PRIMARY CHUTE AND A PRELOADER SAW A BOX LEAKING.  HE TOLD THE SUPERVISOR WHO STOPPED THE BELT AND GOT ME.  WE WENT TOGETHER TO CHECK PACKAGE.  I PUT ON MY PPE-APRON, BOOTS, GLOVES, AND GOGGLES- AND ALSO TOOK RESPONSE SHEETS AND KIT.  WE DETERMINED IT WAS ALCOHOL (ETHANOL 3), ABSORBED LIQUID, AND PUT PACKAGE IN TOTE - CLEANED THE AREA SO WORK COULD RESUME.  UPON INSPECTION OF PACKAGE, ON ONE BOTTLE THE CAP HAD BROKE (SIDE OF CAP STILL SCREWED ON, TOP OF CAP BROKE OFF).  MOST OF THE CONTENTS HAD ALREADY LEAKED AND EVAPORATED. I FINISHED SECURING THE PACKAGE AND PRODUCT AND ABSORBING SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID.  THE CAP MUST HAVE BEEN SCREWED ON TOO TIGHT OR DEFECTIVE- ALSO THERE WAS NO INNER SEAL ON BOTTLE.

ON 5/22/98 A ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CHARLES JONES AND MARTIN CLINEE RESPONDED. THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND 3 PIECE SHIPMENT OF RESIN SOLUTION. THEY OPENED EACH BOX TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE REPORTED ODOR. TWO OF THE THREE BOXES WERE IN PERFECT CONDITION. THE THIRD BOX CONTAINED 13 INNER BOXES, EACH INNER BOX CONTAINED 5 GLASS TUBES OF RESIN SOLUTION. TWO OF THE GLASS TUBES WERE BROKEN CAUSING THE RELEASE OF THE TUBE CONTENTS AND RELEASE OF AN ODOR. NONE OF THE REMAINING INNER BOXES WERE DAMAGED. ONLY ONE PIECE OF THIS THREE PIECE SHIPMENT LEAKED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKAGED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO DESTINATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. EACH PIECE WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS: RESIN SOLUTION, LTD. QTY. UN1866, CLASS 3 LABELS. FILE NAME: AB01098, SHIPPER: HILTI, AWB# TUL 3520760574 DZU

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING OUTSIDE PACKAGE CAR. 1 QUART CONTAINER INSIDE CARTON HAD PUNCTURED CAP. ALSO CONTRIBUTING TO DAMAGE WAS IMPROPER PACKING OR LABELING (HAZARDOUS) THE COMPLETE 1 QUART WAS DISCOVERED BY FOLLOWING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSED PROCEDURE.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING OUTSIDE PACKAGE CARE. 1 QUART CONTAINER INSIDE CARTON HAD PUNCTURED CAP. ALSO CONTRIBUTING TO DAMAGE WAS IMPROPER PACKING OR LABELING (HAZARDOUS). THE COMPLETE 1 QUART WAS DISPOSED BY FOLLOWING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSED PROCEDURE.

RESPONDED TO SPILL IN SORT ISLE. I USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE. CONTAINERIZED MATERIAL IN DMP BAG. NO ABSORBENT REQUIRED. MATERIAL IN POWDER FORM. DISPOSED OF MATERIAL IN DMP. REMAINDER SENT BACK TO SHIPPER. TIGHTER CAP/TOP WOULD HAVE AVOIDED SPILL.

ON MAY 20, 1998, FRA INSPECTOR THOMSON OBSERVED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 50142 IN CSXT'S TRAIN Y120 AT MUSKEGON, MI. HE ADVISED THE CREW OF THE CAR'S CONDITION.  THE TRAIN MASTER AT MUSKEGON REPORTED THE CAR WAS SET OUT ON A SIDING AND ASSISTANCE WAS REQUESTED FROM THE CONSIGNEE.  CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY.
